IV. FRESH APPEAL TO MIGHT.

The Roman government had thus reaped all the advantages of the treaty of Caudium, but refused to fulfil its conditions. In such a case either the legions ought to have been replaced in their desperate position, or some compromise, at any rate, ought to have been offered which the Samnites could have accepted. But, whether owing to the fanaticism of Roman national feeling, or to the want os perseverance which the Sam- nites always show in their negotiations‚ neither of these alternatives was adopted. A fresh appeal is made to the god of war, and he decides for the stronger. Nothing can be more complete than the Roman successes as recorded here by Livy.
